				 Siemens gifts 1:1 bonus 
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Mumbai, Nov. 22: Engineering firm Siemens Ltd today announced a bonus issue in the ratio of 1:1, subject to statutory and regulatory approvals.																								The companys net profit rose to Rs 308.6 crore from Rs 136.75 crore for the quarter ended September 2006. 																								Net sales rose 46.68 per cent to Rs 2,188.45 crore from Rs 1,491.9 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous year. Total income increased 43.44 per cent to Rs 2,242.44 crore from Rs 1,563.32 crore in the year-ago period. 																								The company saw a one-time forex gain of Rs 150 crore and earned Rs 52.4 crore from the sale of its subsidiary. 																								Siemens plans to open an R amp;D centre at Kalwa in central Mumbai and a software centre in Maharashtra. Around 1,000 people will be hired at the Kalwa centre. 																								For the year ended September 30, 2007, the company reported a 73 per cent rise in profit before tax at Rs 874 crore against Rs 501 crore a year ago. 																								For the fourth quarter ended September 30, 2007, profit before tax increased 135 per cent to Rs 440 crore from Rs 188 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous fiscal. 																								Higher productivity and the appreciating rupee contributed to the companys robust performance. 																								Our market cap has gone up 16 times in the last four years and we see a consistent quarter-on-quarter growth at a CAGR of 62 per cent going forward, Siemens managing director J. Schubert said. 
